      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently — brisk walk or very slow jog to get the blood flowing. Focus on relaxed breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. If you can't, slow down.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually slow to a walk. Shake out your legs and take a few deep breaths.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk or very easy jog. Add 4–5 dynamic stretches: leg swings, hip circles, and ankle rolls.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes, then do gentle static stretches for calves, quads, and hamstrings. Hold each for 20–30 seconds.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. The goal is simply to accumulate easy time on your feet and build your aerobic base. Resist the urge to push harder — easy running is where fitness is built. At 7:30/km you should feel like you could hold a conversation without gasping. This is exactly where you want to be.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Run-Walk Intervals — Building Stamina\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":420,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute easy walk to warm up the body. Focus on posture — tall spine, relaxed shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":420,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortably brisk pace — slightly faster than your easy pace but still controlled. Think 'I could talk but prefer not to.'\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":1,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog to recover. Use this time to catch your breath fully before the next run segment.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy walk to bring heart rate down. Gentle leg shakes and deep breathing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute walk. Add leg swings (front-to-back and side-to-side) and a few gentle high knees to activate the hips.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes. Stretch calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings. Consider a gentle foam roll of the quads and IT band if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek session introduces a little structure with run-walk intervals. The 3-minute run segments at a slightly brisker pace (around 7:00/km) help develop your aerobic capacity without overloading you. The 1-minute walk recoveries are intentional — use them fully. Over the coming weeks these run segments will grow longer as your fitness improves. This is the session where you'll start to feel yourself getting stronger.\",\"perceived_effort\":5},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run — Building Your Foundation\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":480,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":480,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute walk. This is your long run — there is no rush. Let your body ease into movement.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easiest, most comfortable pace — 8:00/km or even slower is perfectly fine. Walk whenever you need to. The goal is time on feet, not speed. Keep your effort very low and enjoy the run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate come down naturally. This is a great time to reflect on how the run felt.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute walk before you start running. On your long run day, take extra time to do dynamic warm-up movements: leg swings, hip openers, and a few gentle squats to wake up the glutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Do a thorough stretch session today — calves, hamstrings, hip flexors, glutes, and lower back. Spend at least 10 minutes on this. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes of finishing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run — the cornerstone of your 5K training. At 6km this week, you are already running further than your current long run of 5km, which is a meaningful step forward. Keep the pace very easy (8:00/km or slower). It is completely fine to walk sections — many experienced runners use walk breaks on long runs. The purpose of this run is to build your aerobic engine, strengthen your connective tissue, and develop the mental confidence that comes from covering distance. Do not race this run. Slow down if you need to. Enjoy it.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
